SIMPLE: frippery
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frippery
<hw>Frip"per*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>friperie</ets>, fr. <ets>fruper</ets>. See <er>Fripper</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Coast-off clothes.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Secondhand finery; cheap and tawdry
decoration; affected elegance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fond of gauze and French <qex>frippery</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gauzy <qex>frippery</qex> of a French translation.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place where old clothes are sold.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The trade or traffic in old clothes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frippery</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frippery
<hw>Frip"per*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Trifling;
contemptible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fritz out</ent>⟦br⟧
